com.lightysoft.logmx.mgr

Class LogFileManager

  • java.lang.Object
    • com.lightysoft.logmx.mgr.LogFileManager
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    Cloneable
    Direct Known Subclasses:
    LogStreamManager

    public abstract class LogFileManager
extends Object
implements Cloneable
    Abstract class that each LogMX Manager must extend. A Manager is used by LogMX to get the bytes that will be read by the log parser. For example, you can define your own Manager reading log content from a database, an internal system, or anything else.

    This class contains abstract methods to be implemented by Managers, and final methods to be called by Managers.

    • Managers MUST NOT overload their default Constructor (i.e. define a new Constructor with new parameters). Doing so will produce an error when LogMX will try to clone this Manager.
    • Managers may not override their default Constructor (i.e. redefine it, without any parameter). If you override a Constructor, do not allocate resources or perform time-consuming operations in it, since LogMX can call it any time without calling releaseResources().


    Here is how LogMX uses a classic Manager (i.e. not a live stream Manager or an entries-extraction Manager):
    1. Calls init(LogURL, String)
    2. Calls getCurrentURL()
    3. Calls setEncoding() (non-public method used to set the Encoding returned by getEncoding())
    4. Calls prepareForReading()
    5. Calls supportHeaderReading()
    6. Calls readFileHeader(int) (if Manager returned true to supportHeaderReading())
    7. Calls setEncoding() and newEncodingDetected() if a new encoding was detected by LogMX and if Manager supports Encoding auto-detection
    8. Calls readLine() until it returns null
    9. Calls getCurrentFileLastModifDate() periodically (through getCurrentFileInfo())
    10. Calls getCurrentFileSize() periodically (through getCurrentFileInfo())
    11. Calls releaseResources(boolean)

    To support Auto Refresh, a Manager must:
    • return true in supportHeaderReading()
    • return true in supportRandomAccess()
    • implement readFileHeader(int)
    • implement readLineAtOffset(long)
    • implement getCurrentOffset()
    • implement at least one of getCurrentFileSize() or getCurrentFileLastModifDate(). The unimplemented method should always return the same value

    To support Encoding auto-detection, a Manager must:
    • return true in supportHeaderReading()
    • implement readFileHeader(int)

    To support on-the-fly decompression (e.g. ZIP, GZIP, ...), a Manager must (since LogMX v5.2.0):
    • call getDecompressedStream(String, InputStream) with its current input stream as parameter, to get an uncompressed stream to read from
    • call getCompressFormat() to know which compression method is used (e.g. ZIP, GZIP, ...), if any

    To support live stream reading (no random access to a given offset, like when reading sockets, pipe, serial bus, ...), a Manager must (since LogMX v5.2.0):
    • extend LogStreamManager
    • implement LogStreamManager.setHasReadTimeout(boolean) to enable or disable read timeout

    To support log entries extraction (i.e. Manager directly creates log entries without the use of a LogFileParser), a Manager must (since LogMX v5.2.0):
    • return true in supportLogEntriesExtraction()
    • return a valid LogEntriesInfoProvider in getLogEntriesInfoProvider() to provide LogMX with extracted entries extra information (date format, user-defined fields)
    • implement readEntry() to read the next log entry from the underlying resource
    • call createNewEntryForExtraction() to create an instance of a new, initialized log entry instance to enrich in readEntry()

    Here are a few links to get more information on LogMX managers:
    • Manager development guide: https://logmx.com/manager-dev
    • Manager implementation example: "managers/src" directory of your LogMX distribution
    • Manager development forum: https://logmx.com/forum/viewforum.php?f=2
    Since:
    LogMX v1.2.2, Manager Specification Version 1.0
    Author:
    LightySoft

      • READ_MUTEX

        public final Object READ_MUTEX
        Mutex used by LogMX and the Manager to ensure that only one thread makes this Manager read from the underlying resource, at the same time. Managers can synchronize with this Mutex if they don't want getCurrentFileLastModifDate() or getCurrentFileSize() to be called by LogMX during a specific code execution.
        Since:
        LogMX v1.2.4, Manager Specification Version 1.1

      • getURLPattern

        public abstract String getURLPattern()
        Called by LogMX to know how to display a URL handled by this Manager. The syntax is:
        • SimpleText to denote text "SimpleText"
        • {MyParam} to denote the value of LogURLParameter named "MyParam"
        • [SimpleOptionalPart] to denote an optional part containing free text, LogURLParameter value, or both.

        Here are a few examples of patterns this method can return and URLs matching this pattern:
        • scp://{Login}@{Host}:[{Port}:]{File}
          • scp://john@myhost:22:/mydir/myfile.log
          • scp://john@myhost:/myfile.log
        • http://{Host}[:{Port}][/{File}]
          • http://logmx.com:80/myscript.php?p=4
          • http://logmx.com:80/mypage.html
          • http://logmx.com
        Returns:
        URL Pattern used by this Manager
        Since:
        LogMX v1.2.2, Manager Specification Version 1.0 (see ManagerSpecVersion)

      • getShortFilename

        public String getShortFilename()
        Called by LogMX to get a shorter version of current URL, in order to display it in GUI file tab.
        This method is not abstract or final, so that most Managers may not have to override (i.e. redefine) it, but some others can. The default implementation returns null which means that LogMX will guess a shorter version of current URL (like "myfile" for URL "ftp://john@server/mydir/myfile").

        Overriding this method is useful, for example, if URLs can end with some parameters like in "ftp://john@server/mydir/myfile?p=1", so that only "myfile" is displayed in GUI file tab instead of "myfile?p=1".
        Returns:
        Shorter version of current URL (to be displayed in GUI file tab), or null if not implemented (shorter version of URL will be guessed)
        Since:
        LogMX v4.0.0, Manager Specification Version 1.1 (see ManagerSpecVersion)
        See Also:
        getCurrentURL()

      • getCurrentFileLastModifDate

        public abstract long getCurrentFileLastModifDate()
                                          throws Exception
        Called by LogMX to know when the opened resource was modified for the last time.
        The expected result is a standard Java timestamp (number of milliseconds since 01/01/1970, 00:00:00 GMT). For example, if you have a Java Date, you can get such a timestamp using Date.getTime().

        This method may be called periodically, so it should be rather fast (e.g. no socket connection, but fast I/O operations).

        If the Manager is not able to get this timestamp (or if it only implements getCurrentFileInfo() for performances reason) it may return -1, but file-change detection will be affected if getCurrentFileInfo() also returns -1 as timestamp.
        Returns:
        A Java-based timestamp of last modification, or -1 if Manager can't get this timestamp
        Throws:
        Exception - If the Manager should be able to get the timestamp but could not due to an unexpected event (e.g. I/O error, authentication failure, timeout, ...)
        Since:
        LogMX v1.2.2, Manager Specification Version 1.0 (see ManagerSpecVersion)

      • getCurrentFileInfo

        public LogFileInfo getCurrentFileInfo()
                               throws Exception
        Called periodically by LogMX to get the current file size and date.
        This method is not abstract or final, so that most Managers may not have to override (i.e. redefine) it, but some others can. The default implementation returns a LogFileInfo containing the file size and date returned by getCurrentFileSize() and getCurrentFileLastModifDate(). Manager must override this new method if getting the file size and file date are both time-consuming and if they both need a same connection, transaction, context, ... For example, if getting both file size/date can be performed via a single SFTP "STAT" command, the Manager shall override getCurrentFileInfo() so that only one "STAT" command is performed. Note: this method appeared in Manager Specification Version v1.1 is called periodically for file change detection and Auto-Refresh.
        Returns:
        Information on file (current size and date)
        Throws:
        Exception - If the Manager should be able to get file info but could not due to an unexpected event (e.g. I/O error, authentication failure, timeout, ...)
        Since:
        LogMX v1.2.4, Manager Specification Version 1.1 (see ManagerSpecVersion)

      • newEncodingDetected

        public void newEncodingDetected()
        Called by LogMX after prepareForReading() and before readLine() if and only if the encoding to use (to read bytes from the underlying resource) has changed.
        Managers can get this new encoding using getEncoding().

        If the user chose to auto-detect encoding from LogMX GUI, LogMX will perform this auto-detection after the call to prepareForReading(). If the encoding found during this auto-detection is different from the one set while prepareForReading() was called, this method newEncodingDetected() will be called so that the Manager can re-create its Input Stream Reader before readLine() is called.

        Default implementation of this method does nothing. A Manager should override this method if it calls getEncoding() in prepareForReading() to initialize its Input Stream Reader, or if the Input Stream Reader used in readFileHeader(int) is also used in readLine()
        Since:
        LogMX v1.2.4, Manager Specification Version 1.1 (see ManagerSpecVersion)

      • isLiveStream

        public boolean isLiveStream()
        Called by LogMX to know if this Manager reads log entries from a live stream (e.g. socket, serial port, ...)
        If this Manager reads log entries from a live stream, it shall then extend LogStreamManager.

        This default implementation always returns false.

        If true is returned, LogMX will consider that this Manager cannot access random locations in its underlying stream (e.g. no rewind, no look-ahead, no file header, ...), so LogMX will not call methods readFileHeader(int), readLineAtOffset(long), getCurrentOffset().
        Returns:
        true if this Manager reads log entries from a live stream, false if it doesn't.
        Since:
        LogMX v5.2.0, Manager Specification Version 1.2 (see ManagerSpecVersion)

      • supportLogEntriesExtraction

        public boolean supportLogEntriesExtraction()
        Called by LogMX to know if this Manager can extract log entries itself, without the use of any Log Parser (e.g. case of log entries received as a non-textual stream, like when reading a database, or reading binary data).

        This default implementation always returns false.

        If Manager returns true, LogMX will call readEntry() and getLogEntriesInfoProvider() to make the Manager extract entries.
        Returns:
        true if this Manager supports log entries extraction, false if it doesn't.
        Since:
        LogMX v5.2.0, Manager Specification Version 1.2 (see ManagerSpecVersion)

      • getAutoRefreshDelay

        public int getAutoRefreshDelay()
        Called by LogMX to know the delay (in ms) to wait between each automatic refresh, for all logs opened with this LogFileManager.

        If this method returns -1, then LogMX will use the user settings to determine this delay (in Managers Options, several delays are tunable depending on Manager type: local file, socket, others).

        This default implementation always returns -1.
        Returns:
        Delay (in ms), or -1 to use value given by user settings
        Since:
        LogMX v5.4.0

      • readEntry

        public ParsedEntry readEntry()
                      throws Exception
        Called by LogMX to request the Manager to extract the next log entry.

        This default implementation always returns null.

        LogMX will call this method only if Manager returned true in supportLogEntriesExtraction(). Note: the Manager shall use createNewEntryForExtraction() to get an instance of ParsedEntry to enrich.
        Returns:
        Extracted log entry, or null if no entry can be extracted at this time
        Throws:
        Exception - If the Manager couldn't extract the next log entry
        Since:
        LogMX v5.2.0, Manager Specification Version 1.2 (see ManagerSpecVersion)

      • getLogEntriesInfoProvider

        public LogEntriesInfoProvider getLogEntriesInfoProvider()
        Called by LogMX to request the Manager to provide an object that will enrich extracted log entries (like Parsers do): log entry date conversions, user-defined fields management.

        This default implementation always returns null.

        LogMX will call this method only if Manager returned true in supportLogEntriesExtraction(). Note: the Manager shall use createNewEntryForExtraction() to get an instance of ParsedEntry to enrich.
        Returns:
        LogEntriesInfoProvider to be used by LogMX to convert log entry timestamp, and handle user-defined fields
        Since:
        LogMX v5.2.0, Manager Specification Version 1.2 (see ManagerSpecVersion)

      • canUseParser

        public boolean canUseParser(LogFileParser pParser)
        Called by LogMX to know if the given parser can be used to parse the data returned by this LogFileManager.

        If this method returns false, then LogMX will not attempt to parse the logs with the given parser when reading content with this LogFileManager.

        This default implementation always returns true.
        Parameters:
        pParser - Parser that LogMX would like to use to parse logs out of this LogFileManager's returned content
        Returns:
        true if LogMX can attempt to parse logs with the given parser, or false if LogMX should NOT attempt to parse logs with the given parser
        Since:
        LogMX v8.0.0

      • getEncoding

        public final String getEncoding()
        Called by the Manager to get the Encoding to use when reading bytes.
        All Managers should call this method to use the right encoding.
        The returned string is a valid Java encoding you can use for Java API methods, like:
        new InputStreamReader(myStream, getEncoding());
        Returns:
        Encoding name to use
        Since:
        LogMX v1.2.2, Manager Specification Version 1.0 (see ManagerSpecVersion)

      • getOrAskUserPassword

        public final char[] getOrAskUserPassword(String pLogin,
                                         String pHost)
        Called by the Manager to get a user password saved in LogMX password repository, or by asking the user their password if the password is not saved in LogMX password repository yet.
        The password is returned as a  char[]  for security reasons, so that you can flush it efficiently from memory.
        Parameters:
        pLogin - User login
        pHost - Host to access (used to save a password per host, and per protocol using getProtocolName())
        Returns:
        User password (char array for security reasons, so that you can flush it efficiently from memory). Method returns null if password couldn't be retrieved from LogMX password repository, or if user dismissed password request dialog.
        Since:
        LogMX v1.2.2, Manager Specification Version 1.0 (see ManagerSpecVersion)

      • getProxySettings

        public final ProxySettings getProxySettings(String pHost)
        Called by the Manager to get the proxy settings to use to connect to a host, according to LogMX user preferences set in LogMX GUI.

        Note: the returned object does not contain any password, even if a login/password is set for proxy in LogMX preferences (for security reasons).

        Note: since proxy settings also depend on the used protocol (e.g. HTTP, FTP, ...), LogMX gets this protocol by calling getProtocolName() on this Manager.
        Parameters:
        pHost - Host to access
        Returns:
        Proxy settings to use for this Manager and given host
        Since:
        LogMX v4.0.0, Manager Specification Version 1.1 (see ManagerSpecVersion)

        Returns:

      • getDecompressedStream

        public final InputStream getDecompressedStream(String pFileName,
                                               InputStream pInputStream)
        Called by the Manager to get, if needed, a stream of uncompressed data for the specified logs stream (case of file compressed with ZIP, GZIP or others).
        WARNING: As of LogMX v6.0.3, you may want to use getCompressFormatFromFileName(String) and then getDecompressedStream(InputStream, String), instead of this method, because it may be wrong to detect if a decompressed stream is required, after opening an InputStream: if the Manager tries to open this InputStream at an offset different than 0 (e.g. for AutoRefresh or Tail), it will be impossible to construct a decompressed stream from this InputStream (compression algorithms usually need to read the file header before seeking an offset).

        If no compression was detected, the specified InputStream is returned.
        LogMX will consider a file as compressed if its extension matches an handled compression method (see getCompressFormat()).

        Note that user preferences (set in LogMX GUI) can disable all decompression features (see 'General' tab in Options).

        The calling Manager should not have to keep a reference to pInputStream: for example, closing the returned stream will also close the specified underlying stream even if it contains compressed data.
        Parameters:
        pFileName - Log file name (used to recognize compression method in its extension, like .gz, .zip, ...)
        pInputStream - Stream used to read logs from. Decompression process will read from this stream.
        Returns:
        If a known compression method was detected in file name (and user preferences allow decompression), returns a stream that contains the uncompressed data. Else, the specified pInputStream will be returned, as is.
        Since:
        LogMX v5.2.0, Manager Specification Version 1.2 (see ManagerSpecVersion)

      • getCompressFormatFromFileName

        public final String getCompressFormatFromFileName(String pFileName)
        Called by the Manager to know the compression format that should be used for the given file name (guessed from its extension: ZIP, GZIP or others).
        If no compression should be used, then null is returned.
        LogMX will consider a file as compressed if its extension matches an handled compression method (see getCompressFormat()).

        Note that user preferences (set in LogMX GUI) can disable all decompression features (see 'General' tab in Options): in this case, this method returns null.
        Parameters:
        pFileName - Log file name (used to recognize compression method in its extension, like .gz, .zip, ...)
        Returns:
        If a known compression method was detected in file name (and user preferences allow decompression), then returns one of the String constants described in Javadoc of getCompressFormat(), otherwise, returns null
        Since:
        LogMX v6.0.3

      • getDecompressedStream

        public final InputStream getDecompressedStream(InputStream pInputStream,
                                               String pCompressFormat)
        Called by the Manager to get, if needed, a stream of uncompressed data for the specified logs stream and specified compression format.
        If (pInputStream == null), then the specified InputStream is returned.
        Note that user preferences (set in LogMX GUI) can disable all decompression features (see 'General' tab in Options): in this case, the specified InputStream is returned.

        The calling Manager should not have to keep a reference to pInputStream: for example, closing the returned stream will also close the specified underlying stream even if it contains compressed data.
        Parameters:
        pInputStream - Stream used to read logs from. Decompression process will read from this stream.
        pCompressFormat - Compression format to use (one of the String constants described in Javadoc of getCompressFormat(), usually obtained from getCompressFormatFromFileName(String))
        Returns:
        Returns a stream that contains the uncompressed data, or returns the specified InputStream if the given pCompressFormat cannot be used (error while creating decompressed stream, or decompression deactivated in user preferences).
        Since:
        LogMX v6.0.3

      • getCompressFormat

        public final String getCompressFormat()
        Called by the Manager to get the name of the compression method that was detected during previous call to getCompressFormatFromFileName(String) and getDecompressedStream(InputStream, String).
        If the input stream was not considered as compressed, it will return null.

        The possible values that can be returned are:
        • "ZIP"
        • "GZIP"
        • "TAR-GZIP"
        • "BZ2"
        • "TAR-BZ2"
        • "LZMA"
        • "TAR-LZMA"
        • "XZ"
        • "TAR-XZ"
        • "ZLIB"
        Returns:
        Returns the name of the compression method that was detected during previous call to getCompressFormatFromFileName(String) and getDecompressedStream(InputStream, String), or null if the input stream was not considered as compressed (or if getCompressFormatFromFileName(String) was not called yet)
        Since:
        LogMX v5.2.0, Manager Specification Version 1.2 (see ManagerSpecVersion)

      • createNewEntryForExtraction

        protected final ParsedEntry createNewEntryForExtraction()
        Called by the Manager to create and return a new blank log entry to be used by this Manager during entry extraction (see supportLogEntriesExtraction()).

        Managers should not try to directly create entries instead of calling this method.
        Returns:
        New blank Entry to be used by the Manager
        Since:
        LogMX v5.2.0, Manager Specification Version 1.2 (see ManagerSpecVersion)
